06061nam a22006855i 9780822397847DE-B159720210106113355.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210106t19951995ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223978477 a10.1515/97808223978472doi  a(DE-B1597)553037  a(OCoLC)893680816  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aMUS0250002bisacsh04a781.6522000aRepresenting Jazz /cKrin Gabbard. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1995] 4cÂ©1995  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b39 b&w photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Writing the Other History -- tJAZZ IN LITERATURE AND FILM -- tJammin' the Blues, or the Sight of Jazz, 1944 -- tImprovising and Mythmaking in Eudora Welty's "Powerhouse" -- tFabulating Jazz -- tSignifyin(g) the Phallus: Mo' Better Blues and Representations of the Jazz Trumpet -- tJazz Autobiography: Theory, Practice, Politics -- tEXCURSUS: CABIN 1M THE SKY -- tUptown Folk: Blackness and Entertainment in Cabin in the Sky -- tDoubling, Music, and Race in Cabin in the Sky -- tJAZZ AND DANCE -- tDivine Frivolity; Hollywood Representations of the Lindy Hop, 1937-1942 -- tKeeping the Spirit Alive: The Jazz Dance Testament of Mum Dehn -- tPICTURING JAZZ -- tJazz and the New York School -- tThe Tenor's Vehicle: Reading Way Out West -- tVOCALESE: REPRESENTING JAZZ WITH JAZZ -- tPurple Passages or Fiestas in Blue~ Notes Toward an Aesthetic of Vocalese -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTraditional jazz studies have tended to see jazz in purely musical terms, as a series of changes in rhythm, tonality, and harmony, or as a parade of great players. But jazz has also entered the cultural mix through its significant impact on novelists, filmmakers, dancers, painters, biographers, and photographers. Representing Jazz explores the "other" history of jazz created by these artists, a history that tells us as much about the meaning of the music as do the many books that narrate the lives of musicians or describe their recordings.Krin Gabbard has gathered essays by distinguished writers from a variety of fields. They provide engaging analyses of films such as Round Midnight, Bird, Mo' Better Blues, Cabin in the Sky, and Jammin' the Blues; the writings of Eudora Welty and Dorothy Baker; the careers of the great lindy hoppers of the 1930s and 1940s; Mura Dehn's extraordinary documentary on jazz dance; the jazz photography of William Claxton; painters of the New York School; the traditions of jazz autobiography; and the art of "vocalese." The contributors to this volume assess the influence of extramusical sources on our knowledge of jazz and suggest that the living contexts of the music must be considered if a more sophisticated jazz scholarship is ever to evolve. Transcending the familiar patterns of jazz history and criticism, Representing Jazz looks at how the music actually has been heard and felt at different levels of American culture.With its companion anthology, Jazz Among the Discourses, this volume will enrich and transform the literature of jazz studies. Its provocative essays will interest both aficionados and potential jazz fans.Contributors. Karen Backstein, Leland H. Chambers, Robert P. Crease, Krin Gabbard, Frederick Garber, Barry K. Grant, Mona Hadler, Christopher Harlos, Michael Jarrett, Adam Knee, Arthur Knight, James Naremore  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Jan 2021) 0aJazzxAnalysis, appreciation. 0aJazzxHistory and criticism. 0aJazz. 7aMUSIC / Genres & Styles / Jazz.2bisacsh1 aKnee, Adam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKnight, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rela